 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.3.4","title":"[AA-03.1] Build queueing/network-calculus digital twin for runtime hot paths","description":"Model the scheduler, drain, retry, wakeup, and admission paths as an explicit digital twin with service curves, queue approximations, and state variables tied to observed workloads.","design":"Scope:\n- Translate the AA-01 taxonomy into model terms.\n- Capture the dominant queues and service stages that drive p99/p999.\n- Make the twin precise enough for offline policy search but honest about approximation error.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Major runtime paths have named queue and service stages with parameter sources.
2. Twin predictions can be compared against replayed workload evidence with disclosed error bounds.
3. Model artifacts are versioned and linked to workload IDs, snapshot fields, and direct replay commands.
4. Deterministic unit tests, replay-comparator E2E scripts, and structured model-diagnostic logs protect curve composition, serialization, comparator math, and error-budget reporting.","notes":"Primary risk: false precision.\nCountermeasure: publish approximation error and keep direct baseline comparators visible.\nFallback: degrade to simpler stage-by-stage queue accounting where full digital-twin fidelity is unjustified.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"ubuntu","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:19.354736285Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T19:27:42.940026431Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T19:27:42.939996105Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa03-control","alien-artifact","control","performance","runtime-ascension"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:32.804502255Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.2.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:35.326735515Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:19.354736285Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.3.5","title":"[AA-03.2] Synthesize bounded controller artifacts from replay data and state/loss models","description":"Use the digital twin and replay corpus to synthesize bounded controller artifacts for scheduler/admission/retry decisions with explicit state, action, and loss models instead of heuristic knob tuning.","design":"Scope:\n- Define action sets small enough for deterministic runtime evaluation.\n- Compile the chosen policy into artifact tables or small deterministic evaluators.\n- Preserve conservative fallback and explicit comparator baselines.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Each synthesized controller states its states, actions, loss terms, calibration hooks, and budget caps.
2. Generated artifacts are deterministic, versioned, and consumable by the AA-02 artifact system.
3. Before/after results are measured on replay workloads and deterministic shadow or canary E2E scripts against named conservative comparators.
4. Unit tests and structured decision logs protect policy-table determinism, reward/loss computations, chosen action provenance, and fallback readiness.","notes":"Primary risk: offline-optimized policies overfit the replay corpus.\nCountermeasure: keep action sets small, compare against holdout workloads, and require fallback triggers.\nFallback: retain static current scheduler/admission settings.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"ubuntu","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:24.306196138Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T19:45:45.117302742Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T19:45:45.117278286Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa03-control","alien-artifact","control","decision-plane","runtime-ascension"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.2.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:40.342548957Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:24.306196138Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.5","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:37.837033545Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.3.6","title":"[AA-03.3] Validate controller interference, timescale separation, and tail-SLO fallback gates","description":"Explicit validation bead for multi-controller runtime behavior: prove controllers do not create feedback loops, enforce timescale separation, and fail back conservatively when calibration or tail-SLO guardrails break.","design":"Scope:\n- Build interference microbenches and replay tests for interacting controllers.\n- Run sequential-validity checks and drift alarms.\n- Validate that fallback collapses to the conservative controller set without semantic drift.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Deterministic unit and E2E tests cover controller interactions, oscillation hazards, and fallback entry/exit.\n2. Tail-SLO guardrails are exercised under replayed stress and adversarial regime changes.\n3. Structured logs record controller state, calibration, interference verdicts, and fallback causes.\n4. Rollout cannot advance beyond shadow/canary if interference evidence is missing or negative.","notes":"Primary risk: subtle positive-feedback loops.\nCountermeasure: require explicit timescale-separation statements and sequential evidence checks.\nFallback: disable the newer or slower-confidence controller and retain the conservative one.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"ubuntu","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:29.295691517Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T19:57:16.531581346Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T19:57:16.531555849Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa03-control","alien-artifact","control","runtime-ascension","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.2.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:45.369870681Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:52:29.295691517Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.3.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:54:42.852008077Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"asupersync-1508v.4","title":"[AA-04] Kernel Fast Path 2.0","description":"Pursue bounded-latency hot-path improvements for scheduler, wakeup, queue, and reactor operations using progress-bounded structures and cache-local rewrites that do not compromise determinism or safety.","design":"Background:\n- Asupersync already has strong hot-path work, but the next order term is likely tail jitter from synchronization, queue management, and wakeup coordination.\n- This track is where classic extreme optimization and buried systems techniques meet the runtime kernel.\n\nTrack outputs:\n- Feasibility matrix for wait-free/progress-bounded queue candidates.\n- Prototype hot-path redesigns for dispatch, wake, and steal surfaces.\n- Regression pack proving fairness, no-lost-wakeup, and no-leak behavior under the new substrate.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Candidate fast-path structures are compared against the current baseline with explicit tail, throughput, allocation, and complexity data.
2. At least one improved substrate for a core kernel path is implemented behind a conservative fallback seam.
3. Verification covers fairness bounds, lost-wakeup resistance, quiescence, and obligation safety under stressed schedules.
4. Adoption is comparator-driven; no clever structure ships without clear workload wins and rollback simplicity.
5. The track leaves deterministic unit and E2E stress suites, structured performance diagnostics, and exact fallback/rerun commands so kernel improvements are user-beneficial rather than benchmark-only.","notes":"Recommendation card:\n- Change: attack kernel tail jitter at the queue/wake/reactor layer.\n- EV: high but gated by constants and proof burden.\n- Primary risk: implementing a theoretically beautiful structure with worse real constants or unsafe edge cases.\n- Countermeasure: feasibility first, trait-boundary isolation, and retention of the current intrusive path as fallback.\n- Conservative fallback: current scheduler/local-queue/reactor mechanisms remain selectable.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:30.153501041Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T06:56:59.843658874Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","scheduler"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:44:30.153501041Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:45:10.560986969Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
