 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.1","title":"[SUPERSEDED] [AA-04.1] Compare wait-free and progress-bounded kernel substrate candidates","description":"Evaluate the queue, wake, and reactor substrate candidates that could reduce kernel tail jitter: wait-free rings, bounded-progress structures, cache-local shards, and other high-EV contenders.","design":"Scope:\n- Benchmark the current intrusive path against carefully scoped alternatives.\n- Include implementation complexity, memory cost, determinism impact, and unsafe-surface analysis.\n- Produce an adoption wedge rather than a theory-only survey.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Candidate matrix includes throughput, p95/p99, allocation, memory footprint, and safety/proof cost.\n2. At least one candidate is selected or explicitly rejected with evidence.\n3. Bench artifacts are reproducible and tied to AA-01 workloads.\n4. The chosen adoption wedge isolates the new substrate behind a conservative fallback seam.","notes":"Superseded by asupersync-1508v.4.4 after an interrupted shell pass created a duplicate task. Keep this issue only as audit history; the active canonical bead is asupersync-1508v.4.4.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:45.439694345Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:36.823424536Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:36.823304232Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","scheduler"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.1","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:45.439694345Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.2","title":"[SUPERSEDED] [AA-04.2] Prototype shard-local dispatch, wake, and steal-path redesign behind fallback seam","description":"Implement the selected fast-path experiment for one or more core kernel surfaces such as shard-local dispatch, wake coalescing, steal-path routing, or reactor handoff, always behind a reversible seam.","design":"Scope:\n- Land a concrete prototype on a narrow surface.\n- Keep the old path available for direct A/B comparison and rollback.\n- Preserve determinism, single-owner rules, and structured cleanup semantics.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Prototype path is selectable versus the incumbent path without source divergence.\n2. Benchmarks show measurable wins on at least one important workload family.\n3. Unit tests protect ownership, fairness assumptions, and no-lost-wakeup behavior.\n4. Structured logs show which fast path was active and why fallback engaged if it did.","notes":"Superseded by asupersync-1508v.4.5 after an interrupted shell pass created a duplicate task. Keep this issue only as audit history; the active canonical bead is asupersync-1508v.4.5.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:50.419321465Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:41.516185280Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:41.516078993Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","scheduler"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:50.419321465Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.3","title":"[SUPERSEDED] [AA-04.3] Run bounded-latency fairness, wakeup, and no-leak regression pack","description":"Explicit validation bead for the fast-path track: stress fairness bounds, wakeup correctness, quiescence, and obligation safety under the new substrate with deterministic workloads and logs.","design":"Scope:\n- Exercise cancellation storms, steal pressure, wake races, and shutdown.\n- Measure tail behavior before/after on the AA-01 workload corpus.\n- Fail closed on fairness or no-leak regressions even if raw throughput improves.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Deterministic unit tests and E2E scenarios cover fairness, wake races, shutdown, and obligation/quiescence invariants.\n2. Tail tables include p50/p95/p99/p999 deltas versus the incumbent path.\n3. Structured logs record active substrate, workload ID, fairness counters, and fallback activity.\n4. Regression verdicts are reproducible and directly linked to rollback commands.","notes":"Superseded by asupersync-1508v.4.6 after an interrupted shell pass created a duplicate task. Keep this issue only as audit history; the active canonical bead is asupersync-1508v.4.6.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:55.385691943Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:46.238714719Z","closed_at":"2026-03-06T05:58:46.238608332Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["aa04-fast-path","alien-artifact","performance","runtime-ascension","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-1508v.4.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-1508v.4","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-06T05:49:55.385691943Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-1508v.4.4","title":"[AA-04.1] Compare wait-free and progress-bounded kernel substrate candidates","description":"Evaluate the queue, wake, and reactor substrate candidates that could reduce kernel tail jitter: wait-free rings, bounded-progress structures, cache-local shards, and other high-EV contenders.","design":"Scope:\n- Benchmark the current intrusive path against carefully scoped alternatives.\n- Include implementation complexity, memory cost, determinism impact, and unsafe-surface analysis.\n- Produce an adoption wedge rather than a theory-only survey.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Candidate matrix includes throughput, p95/p99, allocation, memory footprint, determinism impact, and safety/proof cost.
